    <title>Combined summary - Suggestion to remove word from BIP39 English wordlist</title>
    <updated>2023-06-12T23:41:34.831544+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2018-January/015533.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In the world of cryptocurrencies, a phrase is used to verify transactions and hold private keys. This phrase contains words from a 2048 list, which is necessary for verification. However, there have been concerns about using specific words in the list, such as the word "satoshi," which poses an unnecessary security risk. Ronald van der Meer, a reviewer of Bitcoin Improvement Proposals, has suggested removing the word "satoshi" from the BIP39 English wordlist to make it less obvious that it is a bitcoin seed when found by a malicious third party. Weiwu Zhang via bitcoin-dev also sees this as a reasonable improvement. The concern is that malicious third parties could index what they find and test every occurrence of "satoshi" for a lead to a seed, making it easier to identify a Bitcoin seed if found.The discussion on the Bitcoin development mailing list centered around this suggestion. Some argued that removing a word or changing the list is impossible as verification of an existing mnemonic requires the list. However, one solution proposed is to select another word not on the 2048 list and agree by convention that it represents the same number as 'satoshi' or the original word. This convention would serve as an alternative to BIP0039, which provides a standard for creating deterministic wallets using mnemonic phrases. By selecting an alternative word, users can still create a phrase for verification and holding private keys without relying on the 2048 list. Clancy's proposed solution offers a practical alternative to the current limitations of using a phrase for verification in the cryptocurrency world. With this convention, users can have more flexibility and control over their private keys while maintaining security and convenience.</summary>
